<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And Gwideon, why do you like the idea of all these planes being opened? You're in the minority, but I would love to hear your opinion because it seems a lot of people are afraid to speak up if they like the idea of flag requirements being removed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I am likely in a minority of people who post to message boards.  Heh, I am probably in a minority in my guild on my opinion.  I have access to half of those zones, and a partially complete with all of the keys.  It is correct that a single group can complete most (all if right level and mix).  I just hate to be on a 2:00am and have the one person we could use to fill out a group be unflagged.<br>
<br>
One of our guild members (Razoul) spent considerable time doing many of the quests.  Those that helped he grouped with to get the flags.  It took over a week to find us all on at the same time to complete the turn in.  I could care less about the story line after spending the time I have on getting key pieces.  It is just do A to get B at this point to me.  It is nothing more than a time sink now.  If it were an easy one person quest like the Howling Stones key, I would not see the point in changing it.<br>
<br>
I want to log on and have fun, not spend time coaxing others that doing this or that quest 'might' allow us to have fun in a different spot.<br>
<br>
I would agree that there should be a level limit if you do not have the key.  When the quests became a group effort, you could still get a unskilled player into the zone.  Even if you get the access through the primary method of killing the mini, I still meet nasty people in the zones. *shrug*<br>
<br>
Even though PoP was geared toward the high end player, still the standard responce to 'level or AA' was level &gt; all.  Now some who have leveled are going: Now what?  I am limited to 4 to 7 zones and those are getting old quick.<br>
<br>
Smaller guilds have been shaken by PoP.  A division between those that want to see more and those that just want to get on for a few hours here and there have caused a rift.  Many of more former guildmates have said, and I agree, that this was due in part to flagging and PoP.<br>
<br>
It bugs me a little that many want to draw the line just below them.  I had to go through it so....  If it were not difficult in the first place, I don't think anyone would care.  Who now cares that you no longer have to have the tooth in CS to port there?   I don't like time sinks; I can and probably still will do the quests for the keys if the reward is still there for future people that complete them.  Now the shammy/cleric/tank/... that plays at odd times and is skilled but never had a chance to group up for a key can join us.  I like that.<br>
<br>
I think that for a short time the newly opened planes will be crowed with some inexperienced players.  In time they will die enough, and move to appropriate zones for thier skills.  When they open up the old worlds to higher experience it will hopefully spread people out more, and you should see less crowding.  What attracted many to Kanor's and Maiden's Eye, where that they were easy exp.  When the inexperienced player finds that that is not the case, they will probably move.<br>
<br>
Gwideon<br>
PHENOMENAL COSMIC POWER!<br>
in an itty bitty living space<br>
